  "text": "The survival and activity of individual bioaugmentation had not been monitored in several previous applications of the fungal bioaugmentation for enhanced degradation of environmental pollutants [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . We deduce that the slow growth of P. chrysosporium is the reason why it did not persist in the AS system. The AS system was dominated by bacteria ( Fig. 3) , and P. chrysosporium has few advantages over the majority of bacteria with a higher reproduction rate in the ecological competition occurring in AS, which might result in its gradual disappearance.",
